T*
(A common failure mode after a successful architecture cleanup is gradual regression. To avoid) Tj
T*
(that, the team should adopt a maintenance policy that preserves the gains:) Tj
T*
(- every new backend mutation feature must name its owner explicitly) Tj
T*
(- every new query surface must declare revision and freshness semantics) Tj
T*
(- every new long-running operation must expose lifecycle state or events) Tj
T*
(- every new storage access point must justify why it is not going through a repository or) Tj
T*
(service interface) Tj
T*
(- every new GUI feature must go through the GUI state store rather than bypassing it with local) Tj
T*
(transport logic) Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
(This policy turns the refactor program into a durable operating standard instead of a one-time) Tj
T*
(clean sweep.) Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
(Code-review heuristics for the post-refactor architecture) Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
(Reviewers should ask a stable set of questions on every significant change:) Tj
T*
(- Did the change introduce a second owner for an existing mutation domain?) Tj
T*
(- Did it move any authority into the GUI or API that should remain in backend services?) Tj
T*
(- Did it make read consistency harder to describe?) Tj
T*
(- Did it increase or decrease rollback difficulty?) Tj
T*
(- Did it add observability proportional to the new complexity it introduced?) Tj
T*
(- Did it preserve the distinction between policy, convenience logic, and canonical truth?) Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
(These heuristics are especially important in a blockchain codebase because small ergonomic) Tj
T*
(shortcuts can become long-lived architectural liabilities very quickly.) Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
(Twelve-month target behavior) Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
(Twelve months after the refactor program begins, the healthiest outcome is not that the codebase) Tj
T*
(has been endlessly restructured. The healthiest outcome is that the refactoring rate slows) Tj
T*
(because the architecture is stable enough that routine development no longer requires) Tj
T*
(cross-cutting cleanup.) Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
(At that point, the team should ideally experience:) Tj
T*
(- fewer architectural regressions from routine feature work) Tj
T*
(- lower debugging time for wallet and lifecycle issues) Tj
T*
(- far less ambiguity during restart, upgrade, or network-switch investigations) Tj
T*
(- a smaller set of engineers needing to work inside the protected consensus core) Tj
T*
(- stronger confidence that consensus-sensitive work can be isolated, reviewed, and tested) Tj
T*
(deliberately) Tj
T*
() Tj
