() Tj
T*
(Stewardship note) Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
(The final responsibility of this program is stewardship. The team is not only cleaning code; it) Tj
T*
(is deciding which parts of the system deserve stability, which parts deserve isolation, and) Tj
T*
(which parts deserve stronger proof before anyone touches them again. In a blockchain system,) Tj
T*
(that judgment is part of the architecture itself.) Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
(That is why the roadmap repeatedly chooses discipline over bravado: fewer hidden owners, fewer) Tj
T*
(implied transitions, fewer unreviewable side effects, and fewer reasons for a routine product) Tj
T*
(change to drift into protocol risk.) Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
(It also explains the central posture of the document: clean the outer layers first, make the) Tj
T*
(runtime understandable, make the data paths explicit, and spend consensus risk only when the) Tj
T*
(evidence says there is no cheaper safe path left.) Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
(If the team keeps that posture, future architecture decisions should become easier, not harder,) Tj
T*
(because the system will offer clearer evidence about where truth lives, where complexity is) Tj
T*
(justified, and where simplification is finally safe.) Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
(That, more than any diagram or naming scheme, is what separates a temporary cleanup from a) Tj
T*
(durable production architecture that can absorb new features, new operators, and new stresses) Tj
T*
(without losing its center.) Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
(Final close) Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
(The safest path to a production-grade Atho is not to make the system look perfectly modern on) Tj
T*
(paper. It is to make the current system more legible, more deterministic, more observable, and) Tj
T*
(more disciplined about ownership while protecting the protocol core from unnecessary turbulence.) Tj
T*
(If the roadmap stays faithful to that principle, the codebase can become dramatically cleaner) Tj
T*
(and easier to operate without paying for that improvement in consensus risk.) Tj
T*
ET
endstream
